01:16:20.440 --> 01:16:23.160
I'll give you an example of something that I think was very successful.

01:16:23.160 --> 01:16:25.920
I was part of something for a few summers.

01:16:25.920 --> 01:16:28.560
I wish it was still ongoing.

01:16:28.560 --> 01:16:36.960
Called the NASA and the Navajo Nation Summer Space Camp with middle school students.

01:16:36.960 --> 01:16:37.960
And we collaborated.

01:16:37.960 --> 01:16:39.680
We had a few NASA scientists.

01:16:39.680 --> 01:16:48.800
I was one of them and a few Navajo elders and a medicine man and about 20 middle schoolers.

01:16:48.800 --> 01:16:53.400
And we spent a couple weeks traveling around the Navajo Nation together going to different

01:16:53.400 --> 01:17:01.320
landscapes, learning the cultural stories of the land, teaching our perspective on the

01:17:01.320 --> 01:17:06.240
scientific stories of the land, listening a lot, everybody learning a lot.

01:17:06.240 --> 01:17:12.880
And then in the middle school kids synthesized all of this with art projects in which they

01:17:12.880 --> 01:17:19.280
combined the stories, the scientific and the cultural stories.

01:17:19.280 --> 01:17:21.360
And they were really, really powerful.

01:17:21.360 --> 01:17:24.560
Like one group of, and the kids collaborated to do this.

01:17:24.560 --> 01:17:29.040
So one group of middle school kids made a, you know, the Navajo cradle boards when a

01:17:29.040 --> 01:17:31.120
child was born is this whole symbolic thing.

01:17:31.120 --> 01:17:35.360
So they made the cradle board, but it was also the story of the universe with, you know,

01:17:35.360 --> 01:17:37.040
the big bang and all this stuff.

01:17:37.040 --> 01:17:41.920
And another group of these middle school kids, they synthesized this volcanic site we went

01:17:41.920 --> 01:17:44.640
to, which we told them about basalt flows and this and that.

01:17:44.640 --> 01:17:49.000
But their traditional story is that the basalt flows are the giant's blood because they're

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:50.480
with these, this battle of giants.

01:17:50.480 --> 01:17:54.840
So they did this diorama that had the giants battling in their blood spilling out.

01:17:54.840 --> 01:17:56.600
And then it was also basalt flow.

01:17:56.600 --> 01:17:59.560
And it was just, it was tremendous.

01:17:59.560 --> 01:18:00.720
We all learned so much.

01:18:00.720 --> 01:18:04.400
But it wouldn't have worked if we had gone in there with the attitude like, these are

01:18:04.400 --> 01:18:05.560
the points we're going to teach.

01:18:05.560 --> 01:18:07.280
And this is our time scale.

01:18:07.280 --> 01:18:10.720
And at the end, you will be able to be quizzed on this knowledge and you'll be able to learn

01:18:10.720 --> 01:18:11.720
it.

01:18:11.720 --> 01:18:13.800
You know, you have to listen and you have to be open to the fact that you're going to

01:18:13.800 --> 01:18:15.800
learn as much as anybody else.

01:18:15.800 --> 01:18:23.040
Just a quick comment about artistic literacy.

01:18:23.040 --> 01:18:27.880
I ran a little round table a couple of years ago about art and science at Emory University.

01:18:27.880 --> 01:18:32.440
And one of the people at the table, the surgeon, and said, you know, well, I'm an artist as

01:18:32.440 --> 01:18:33.440
well.

01:18:33.440 --> 01:18:36.040
I'm an artist at the table got infuriated.

01:18:36.040 --> 01:18:41.760
That's like me saying I've dissected a few frogs, so I'm a surgeon.

01:18:41.760 --> 01:18:48.400
And so without getting into the realm of elitism, I do want to point out that the elephant in

01:18:48.400 --> 01:18:51.560
the room is that art and science are not on a level playing field.

01:18:51.560 --> 01:18:56.160
And an example of that is that we teach science K through 12 and into universities.

01:18:56.160 --> 01:18:59.440
And it's required in most of those grades.

01:18:59.440 --> 01:19:04.560
And we stop teaching art in what, maybe fourth grade depending on the whatever the school

01:19:04.560 --> 01:19:05.680
district is.

01:19:05.680 --> 01:19:09.520
And if you look at funding amounts, the National Endowment for the Arts and National Science

01:19:09.520 --> 01:19:14.960
Foundation, you can add zeros to NSF and to DARPA grants.

01:19:14.960 --> 01:19:17.400
So that's my comment.

01:19:17.400 --> 01:19:25.120
So my question, sort of reflection, is sort of picking up at this topic of listening.

01:19:25.120 --> 01:19:29.400
I'm starting up an art and science residency program in the Appalachians called Art Science

01:19:29.400 --> 01:19:31.120
in Field as if center.

01:19:31.120 --> 01:19:32.600
You can go there as if dot center.

01:19:32.600 --> 01:19:34.360
Our residency program starts this March.

01:19:34.360 --> 01:19:36.520
That's my little plug.

01:19:36.520 --> 01:19:41.220
And it's in a sort of cosmopolitan part of the Appalachian that's very near to Pennland

01:19:41.220 --> 01:19:44.640
School of Crafts, where right over the mountains from where Black Mountain College used to

01:19:44.640 --> 01:19:48.000
be, Matthew Schline was actually at Pennland this summer.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:51.320
There are a lot of makers in the area that come from other places.

01:19:51.320 --> 01:19:55.840
But nevertheless, that 48% of people who don't believe in evolution, a lot of those people

01:19:55.840 --> 01:19:57.200
are my neighbors.

01:19:57.200 --> 01:19:59.160
And so it presents a problem.

01:19:59.160 --> 01:20:00.800
I don't want to exist in a vacuum.

01:20:00.800 --> 01:20:06.080
I don't want to be this jewel of wonderfulness in the middle of, quote unquote, nowhere.

01:20:06.080 --> 01:20:09.560
I want to actually have relationships with the community.

01:20:09.560 --> 01:20:14.920
And so one of the things I'm thinking about approaching this is, well, there are three

01:20:14.920 --> 01:20:15.920
things.

01:20:15.920 --> 01:20:18.200
This is an area that's sort of tribal.

01:20:18.200 --> 01:20:19.560
I thought, you know, I'm from the south.

01:20:19.560 --> 01:20:22.640
I can just breeze right in and I'll blend in after a couple of years.

01:20:22.640 --> 01:20:27.000
But actually, people have been in that community for like eight to ten generations.

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:28.200
They all know each other.

01:20:28.200 --> 01:20:30.840
They're like 30 last names that are in the county.

01:20:30.840 --> 01:20:35.440
And there's like this real sense of, you know, not from here.

01:20:35.440 --> 01:20:38.160
And so there's this tribalism.

01:20:38.160 --> 01:20:42.440
And I've thought like finding an ally within the community who's from there who can sort

01:20:42.440 --> 01:20:47.960
of like help to, you know, approach people and help tell our story and present our work

01:20:47.960 --> 01:20:49.280
is a real important thing.

01:20:49.280 --> 01:20:54.640
And then the other two things are that people are more the older generations than younger

01:20:54.640 --> 01:20:55.640
generations.

01:20:55.640 --> 01:20:57.960
They're tied to the land, tied to place.

01:20:57.960 --> 01:21:03.760
And that's a lot of what this art science center is about is like art science plus nature,

01:21:03.760 --> 01:21:08.000
you know, being this southern Appalachians, which is incredibly biologically diverse and

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:09.200
interesting geology.

01:21:09.200 --> 01:21:12.800
So that pride of place is another way to tap in.

01:21:12.800 --> 01:21:16.400
And the third one is that, you know, there's a sense of independence.

01:21:16.400 --> 01:21:22.760
And like as much as people from that region are they value authority from the church,

01:21:22.760 --> 01:21:25.560
they do not value authority from the federal government.

01:21:25.560 --> 01:21:29.800
And this kind of goes back to their Scottish roots and, you know, a lot of history.

01:21:29.800 --> 01:21:35.280
But that sense of DIY that, you know, makers have and that scientists have and trying to

01:21:35.280 --> 01:21:36.280
use that.

01:21:36.280 --> 01:21:43.080
And so I guess my question is like looking for wisdom about dealing with difficult, almost

01:21:43.080 --> 01:21:49.520
sometimes hostile audiences to science and like what are some approaches for tackling

01:21:49.520 --> 01:21:51.120
that challenge?

01:21:51.120 --> 01:21:58.120
Anybody up for it?

01:21:58.120 --> 01:22:05.840
There is a growing literature on this that is run by people who describe themselves as

01:22:05.840 --> 01:22:09.120
studying the science of science communication.

01:22:09.120 --> 01:22:14.640
Dan Kahan, Yale, I am utterly blanking on everyone else's name, but he has a blog where

01:22:14.640 --> 01:22:15.640
he lists these people.

01:22:15.640 --> 01:22:21.520
And there's no magic bullet, of course.

01:22:21.520 --> 01:22:23.440
You know, it's lots and lots and lots of hard work.

01:22:23.440 --> 01:22:25.520
But they have identified things.

01:22:25.520 --> 01:22:30.240
And it's like David's point or no, sorry, Stuart's point about people actually do understand

01:22:30.240 --> 01:22:31.320
how evolution works.

01:22:31.320 --> 01:22:37.080
And so learning things like, you know, if your approach is to teach them evolution, you're

01:22:37.080 --> 01:22:38.240
going to fail.

01:22:38.240 --> 01:22:39.920
And so they've learned a number of things like this.

01:22:39.920 --> 01:22:46.920
And to be honest, it feels like they're about 2% of the way we need to be, but it's growing.

01:22:46.920 --> 01:22:53.200
I feel like we need a panel just for that question.

01:22:53.200 --> 01:22:54.200
Honestly.

01:22:54.200 --> 01:22:56.080
I'm Patricia Miranda.

01:22:56.080 --> 01:22:58.720
I'm an artist and an educator and curator.

01:22:58.720 --> 01:23:03.000
I've done a lot of work with my own work with art and science.

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:08.160
And I teach in a BFA and MFA program and also develop K through 12 programming, steam-based

01:23:08.160 --> 01:23:11.000
programming in New York City and the tri-state area, especially.

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:15.300
But I wanted to just push back a little bit on some of the art conversation, which I thank

01:23:15.300 --> 01:23:20.400
you for Patricia's starting that pushback.

01:23:20.400 --> 01:23:24.280
I felt a little bit like the conversation about art in this panel has been kind of like

01:23:24.280 --> 01:23:27.320
a poor stepchild or the poor relation a little bit.

01:23:27.320 --> 01:23:31.600
And I just want to echo what Patricia was saying about art having a value of its own.

01:23:31.600 --> 01:23:35.400
I think you've mitigated some of those since she got up and said that.

01:23:35.400 --> 01:23:37.600
But I also think this idea of artistic literature.

01:23:37.600 --> 01:23:42.120
I want to, literacy, I want to push back on that too with all due respect.

01:23:42.120 --> 01:23:43.320
I don't think it's the artist's fault.

01:23:43.320 --> 01:23:47.200
I don't think that artists are making art about art and that that's an isolated thing.

01:23:47.200 --> 01:23:51.880
I think that the aesthetic and the formal are always unfolded by the social throughout

01:23:51.880 --> 01:23:54.320
history in every instance of art making.

01:23:54.320 --> 01:23:58.840
So those frescoes that you may, that we may not understand is not necessarily only because

01:23:58.840 --> 01:24:02.760
we may not understand all of the Christian symbolism, but also because it's unfolded

01:24:02.760 --> 01:24:04.560
by the social of the time.

01:24:04.560 --> 01:24:08.400
And so there's an entire culture built into those paintings which were didactic and they

01:24:08.400 --> 01:24:13.320
had certain functions that it's invisible to us and we'll never know because we can't

01:24:13.320 --> 01:24:16.480
enter a medieval mind or Renaissance mind.

01:24:16.480 --> 01:24:20.840
And I would also say that I could take any of you to Chelsea tomorrow and give you an

01:24:20.840 --> 01:24:24.680
well, tomorrow, not tomorrow, it's Sunday, but I could take you to through Chelsea and

01:24:24.680 --> 01:24:29.440
show you artists that are deeply, deeply engaged with the issues of the day and that

01:24:29.440 --> 01:24:33.280
maybe it's not getting out into the mainstream culture in that direct way, but it filters

01:24:33.280 --> 01:24:38.600
down even to like Doho Se's painting work appearing in like a Drake video or something

01:24:38.600 --> 01:24:39.600
like that.

01:24:39.600 --> 01:24:43.000
So I think that there are artists that are in conversation with each other, they're in

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:47.720
their conversation with art history and they're in a conversation with all of culture.

01:24:47.720 --> 01:24:50.800
So you can just think of the Carol Walker, sorry not the Carol Walker.

01:24:50.800 --> 01:24:53.760
Well, yes, you can think of Carol Walker as an artist who's done that, but the Dana

01:24:53.760 --> 01:24:59.520
Schutz Emmett Till painting controversy if you know about that or the Sam Durant scaffolding

01:24:59.520 --> 01:25:03.840
at the Walker Art Museum, these are two things that created enormous, enormous discourse

01:25:03.840 --> 01:25:05.720
that bled out.

01:25:05.720 --> 01:25:09.880
Maybe it is this kind of core community that's having the depth of the conversation, but

01:25:09.880 --> 01:25:14.400
it does filter out and I've had these conversations with my students over and over again.

01:25:14.400 --> 01:25:19.120
So framing it as the aesthetic and the formula always unfolded by the social is one of the

01:25:19.120 --> 01:25:20.960
sort of pedagogies that I've developed.

01:25:20.960 --> 01:25:24.600
And I developed a pedagogy of critique based on, you know, critique is something that in

01:25:24.600 --> 01:25:27.640
the art world we do all the time.

01:25:27.640 --> 01:25:31.840
But to help artists and professional artists I work with a lot in developing a critical

01:25:31.840 --> 01:25:37.160
language to be able to communicate what they're doing in their work without it dissecting,

01:25:37.160 --> 01:25:39.280
trying to do the thing where you're like, what does this mean?

01:25:39.280 --> 01:25:40.280
Well, who cares?

01:25:40.280 --> 01:25:41.280
Right?

01:25:41.280 --> 01:25:44.000
It's not about why, it's never about why, it's about what?

01:25:44.000 --> 01:25:45.000
What is happening?

01:25:45.000 --> 01:25:46.000
What is the art doing?

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:48.120
Because even a painting on the wall is a verb, right?

01:25:48.120 --> 01:25:50.800
It's in action, it's in dialogue and it's in discourse.

01:25:50.800 --> 01:25:54.800
And I think that people don't understand that about art, not because artists are not doing

01:25:54.800 --> 01:25:59.800
it, but because we don't teach art in the schools in such a way that discourse like

01:25:59.800 --> 01:26:04.640
someone just said before that science is taught K through 12 and art is not.

01:26:04.640 --> 01:26:09.040
So it's a constant, constant conversation that we're having.

01:26:09.040 --> 01:26:13.560
And I think in the pedagogy that I work in, it is about developing a critical language

01:26:13.560 --> 01:26:19.160
that communicates those things without dissecting them into sort of, you know, if you dissect

01:26:19.160 --> 01:26:21.120
the frog you understand the frog, right?

01:26:21.120 --> 01:26:22.120
We don't.

01:26:22.120 --> 01:26:24.120
You can dissect the frog and understand many things, but you still don't understand the

01:26:24.120 --> 01:26:25.920
frog, so the same thing is true of art.

01:26:25.920 --> 01:26:28.640
So I just wanted to push back on that.

01:26:28.640 --> 01:26:30.640
Sure, sure, sure, absolutely.

01:26:30.640 --> 01:26:35.240
We'll have a good short time.

01:26:35.240 --> 01:26:38.440
Yeah, let me briefly comment on that.

01:26:38.440 --> 01:26:44.520
So you know, I completely agree, I was speaking specifically to science literacy among, sorry,

01:26:44.520 --> 01:26:46.920
artistic literacy among scientists.

01:26:46.920 --> 01:26:49.920
So you know, it is certainly true, I mean, there are many-

01:26:49.920 --> 01:26:51.640
But that's a cultural thing, right?

01:26:51.640 --> 01:26:56.720
It's not embedded in the culture of education in a way that a scientist would come up.

01:26:56.720 --> 01:27:02.400
So I worked in Europe this past last semester and it is much more-

01:27:02.400 --> 01:27:06.120
Art's not perfect, of course, but much more embedded in the culture that people are learning

01:27:06.120 --> 01:27:09.240
about art the same way they're learning about wine or food, you know what I mean?

01:27:09.240 --> 01:27:15.000
It's considered this kind of larger conversation that you're all a part of as a citizen.

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:16.160
And so, yeah.

01:27:16.160 --> 01:27:18.320
It's not here.

01:27:18.320 --> 01:27:22.960
It's very siloed, you know.

01:27:22.960 --> 01:27:25.080
Hey, hello.

01:27:25.080 --> 01:27:31.480
So I wanted to push on for a second the society part of this panel and, specifically, unfortunately,

01:27:31.480 --> 01:27:36.480
politics.

01:27:36.480 --> 01:27:46.000
So as was just said, artists are very engaged in political issues these days and more than

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:47.160
ever.

01:27:47.160 --> 01:27:52.640
But I'm curious, my question for the panel is, what is the responsibility, the unique

01:27:52.640 --> 01:27:56.240
responsibility of scientists politically?

01:27:56.240 --> 01:28:03.080
In my opinion, very quickly, is- There's sort of too often a sort of view from nowhere

01:28:03.080 --> 01:28:07.640
in neutrality that's mixed with a little bit of elitism.

01:28:07.640 --> 01:28:13.600
And I worry sometimes that the best we can do is like make signs for the climate march

01:28:13.600 --> 01:28:20.480
and get out in kind of a way that could be construed as elitism when you're just sort

01:28:20.480 --> 01:28:23.520
of presenting the facts and hoping for the best.

01:28:23.520 --> 01:28:29.080
And then one other example I want to mention was last year during the campaign, the heat

01:28:29.080 --> 01:28:35.200
of the campaign, Neil deGrasse Tyson, made this unfortunate idea, I think, called- Why

01:28:35.200 --> 01:28:39.000
why don't we all just live in a world called Rachinalia?

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:44.320
And then I think some of the new atheist people made T-shirts and it was this whole thing.

01:28:44.320 --> 01:28:45.320
Like really?

01:28:45.320 --> 01:28:48.120
Okay, so anyway, that's my question for you guys.

01:28:48.120 --> 01:28:52.760
I thought that was bad and I think it speaks to a certain kind of elitism that was talked

01:28:52.760 --> 01:28:54.160
about earlier.

01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:59.560
What should scientists be doing politically or what should they not be doing?

01:28:59.560 --> 01:29:05.200
Yeah, it's a fair question and it's a difficult one, of course, and something I- A lot of my

01:29:05.200 --> 01:29:10.040
colleagues have been involved in discussions of that for a long time and you're right,

01:29:10.040 --> 01:29:14.840
we were sort of trained, brought up with this idea that science is value neutral, which

01:29:14.840 --> 01:29:17.240
of course is- it's not.

01:29:17.240 --> 01:29:21.920
And it gets us off the hook in a way that we're really not.

01:29:21.920 --> 01:29:24.960
But the opposite extreme of that is an interesting question.

01:29:24.960 --> 01:29:28.320
Should scientists be activists?

01:29:28.320 --> 01:29:31.400
And there's danger there too.

01:29:31.400 --> 01:29:36.200
You don't want to enslave your- when you're actually practicing science, you don't want

01:29:36.200 --> 01:29:40.880
to enslave, you don't want to have an outcome that you're seeking to try to make a point.

01:29:40.880 --> 01:29:45.040
I can give you examples of science that is aired in that way because- oh, if I only had

01:29:45.040 --> 01:29:48.440
this result, it would help strengthen this political thing that I think is important.

01:29:48.440 --> 01:29:49.720
That's dangerous too.

01:29:49.720 --> 01:29:54.080
So there's no simple answer to this, but it's obviously not we just pretend we're from

01:29:54.080 --> 01:29:56.720
on high disengaged.

01:29:56.720 --> 01:30:06.440
One thing that I will say is that there is a genuine power and I think radicalism to

01:30:06.440 --> 01:30:10.240
telling the truth about the world the way we really see it.

01:30:10.240 --> 01:30:15.720
In other words, when you see the Earth from space, you don't see national borders.

01:30:15.720 --> 01:30:24.280
You know that macroeconomics as it is described by economists is wrong fundamentally because

01:30:24.280 --> 01:30:29.920
it doesn't include ecology and notions of natural limits and so forth.

01:30:29.920 --> 01:30:37.560
You understand that the world is a place of deep cycling, of elements and energy that

01:30:37.560 --> 01:30:40.200
we're embedded in those cycles.

01:30:40.200 --> 01:30:45.480
So there is a radicalness to just simply teaching things about the world that we've learned

01:30:45.480 --> 01:30:49.640
that we need to integrate to be successful as a species.

01:30:49.640 --> 01:30:52.920
And if that's a political act, then I'm guilty of it.

01:30:52.920 --> 01:30:54.680
Something very quickly about this?

01:30:54.680 --> 01:30:55.680
Okay, very quickly.

01:30:55.680 --> 01:30:56.680
We're at time.

01:30:56.680 --> 01:31:00.040
I actually don't agree with you largely about this.

01:31:00.040 --> 01:31:05.480
Some of it's okay, but I think the job of science and society now is to be optimistic.

01:31:05.480 --> 01:31:10.400
That may sound like a crazy thing to say today, but I think we completely blew the climate

01:31:10.400 --> 01:31:11.400
change thing.

01:31:11.400 --> 01:31:15.280
I think it's a scientist fault that it's as screwed up as it is because we took this

01:31:15.280 --> 01:31:21.960
thing, we have made it a kind of a finger wagging problematic issue for everybody.

01:31:21.960 --> 01:31:25.160
You've got to get on board with this or there's something wrong with you.

01:31:25.160 --> 01:31:27.520
My opinion is we should have said, you know what?

01:31:27.520 --> 01:31:31.760
We have these amazing new technologies from space and geology and elsewhere.

01:31:31.760 --> 01:31:34.000
We have learned that the planet is warming up.

01:31:34.000 --> 01:31:35.920
This is potentially dangerous.

01:31:35.920 --> 01:31:36.920
Guess what?

01:31:36.920 --> 01:31:37.920
We're great at this.

01:31:37.920 --> 01:31:38.920
We can solve this.

01:31:38.920 --> 01:31:39.920
We got to the moon.

01:31:39.920 --> 01:31:40.920
We can solve this too.

01:31:40.920 --> 01:31:42.360
